## Chapter 2: The Reality of the Bottom Tier
The journey to Anvil Ridge Vocational Academy felt less like a commute to higher education and more like a exile.
Kaelen leaned his forehead against the vibrating, scratched glass of the district transit rail. The gleaming skyscrapers of the Upper Core—with their gravity-defying architecture and ambient mana fields—had long faded behind a horizon of smog. Here in the Outer Rim, the buildings were grey, functional concrete blocks, stained dark by decades of industrial soot and the acidic rainfall that bled off the nearby Colony Zone borders.
When the train screeched to a halt at the final station, the automated doors groaned open, letting in the heavy scent of burning oil and stagnant water.
Kaelen stepped onto the platform, shoulder bag slung over his arm. A rusted iron archway stood over the station exit, the words *Anvil Ridge Technical & Auxiliary Vocational* barely legible beneath coats of peeling green paint.
The "campus" was a singular, massive five-story complex wrapped in chain-link fence topped with razor wire. There were no holographic training grounds, no soaring spires, and certainly no state-of-the-art medical bays. It looked like an old manufacturing plant because it *used* to be one, before the city government converted it to house the dregs of the Manifestation ceremonies.
The main courtyard was sparse. A few dozen students loitered on the cracked asphalt, their faces wearing variations of the same expression Kaelen had seen in the mirror: a mix of numbness and lingering resentment. These were the Tier-E and Tier-D rejects. The *Sentries* who would spend their lives guarding empty warehouses, the *Logistics Assistants* destined for data entry, and the *Scrappers* who would clean the streets.
Kaelen navigated the dim, fluorescent-lit corridors to the main auditorium for the mandatory orientation. The room was freezing, the heating vents overhead rattling loudly without producing much actual warmth.
At the podium stood a man with a severe limp, his left arm completely replaced by a heavy, unpolished cybernetic prosthetic that looked decades out of date. His face was a map of scar tissue, and his eyes held the hollow, deadened stare of someone who had looked into the abyss of the trenches and never quite looked away.
"Sit down and shut up," the man said. He didn't use a microphone, but his voice carried a harsh, raspy gravel that instantly silenced the room.
He leaned heavily against the podium, surveying the sea of uniform jackets. "I am Instructor Horgan. I am a retired Tier-C *Vanguard Skirmisher*. Key word is *retired*. I am not here to hold your hands, and I am not here to give you inspirational speeches. The elite academies teach their students how to become heroes. Anvil Ridge teaches you how not to die in a ditch."
Horgan tapped a console, and a basic, flickering projection appeared behind him, displaying a breakdown of the curriculum. It was incredibly brief.
"Most of you have awakened auxiliary classes. That means the city views you as resource units, not combat assets. Your classes will consist of basic physical conditioning, low-tier survival theory, and occupational training for factory and sanitation placement. The government provides you with a roof over your heads in the West Barracks, basic nutrient paste rations, and exactly zero financial stipends."
A murmur of discontent rippled through the freshmen. A student a few rows ahead of Kaelen raised his hand. "Sir, what about training gear? Or essence crystals for skill leveling?"
Horgan let out a short, mocking bark of laughter. "Gear? Crystals? You think corporate sponsors are pouring money into a vocational school? If you want gear, you buy it. If you want resources, you earn them. The city allocates a baseline auxiliary bounty board in the lower levels. Take odd jobs, clear mutant pests, sweep up debris after the real Hunters do their work. You get paid in pennies, but those pennies buy your bread. If you don't like it, the exit gates are open. You can go sleep in the gutter."
He straightened up, his cybernetic arm clicking mechanically. "Dismissed. Go find your assigned bunks. Class starts at dawn, and I do not tolerate lateness."
The West Barracks were exactly as bleak as advertised. Kaelen’s assigned room was a concrete cell shared with three other guys. It contained four iron bunk beds, thin mattresses, and a communal bathroom down the hall that smelled strongly of rust.
His roommates were already wallowing in their own misery, whispering quietly about appeals, system re-evaluations, or trying to find factory apprenticeships early just to drop out. Kaelen didn't join the conversation. He dropped his bag on the top bunk, sat down, and pulled up his status interface.
The normal screen was still there—drab gray, listing his pathetic baseline attributes. But when he focused his mind entirely on the metallic sensation still humming deep within his right palm, the faint, blood-red text bled into the corners of his vision.
**[Target criteria expanded: Material components, Organic matter, Crystallized Essence.]**
Kaelen stared at his hand. He needed to test this. If he stayed within the school's routine, he would spend four years learning how to sort scrap metal at a 40% efficiency rate, graduate as a Tier-E nobody, and live a life completely exposed to the whims of the high-tier elites who ruled the city. The threat of being taken by a corporate lab or locked in a guild research black site was absolute if anyone caught a glimpse of his glitch.
He had to be smart. He had to look completely ordinary. He needed to be the broke, struggling Tier-E student who barely passed his classes, while using the cover of the bottom-tier academy's complete lack of supervision to build his foundation.
Leaving the barracks, Kaelen headed down to the basement level of the main building, where the Auxiliary Guild board was located.
The basement was a damp, low-ceilinged room with a single automated terminal blinking in the center. A few older students were hanging around, looking over the listings with bored, tired expressions.
Kaelen walked up to the terminal and swiped his student ID card. The screen refreshed, displaying a list of low-priority, low-pay tasks that the primary Hunter Guilds didn't even bother to catalog.
 * **Task 042:** *Sewer Filtration Pipe Debris Clearing. Reward: 15 Credits.*
 * **Task 089:** *Warehouse District Scavenge & Sorting (Post-Breach Containment). Reward: 20 Credits.*
 * **Task 114:** *Sub-basement Pest Eradication (Mutant Vermin/Imp Infestation). Area: Sector 9 Disused Cold Storage. Reward: 30 Credits.*
Kaelen’s eyes locked onto Task 114.
*Mutant Vermin and Imps.* Low-level organic monsters. The kind that elite teams killed by the hundreds without looking back, leaving the carcasses to rot or be burned by sanitation squads because their aetheric fragments were too small and low-grade to be worth the time it took to harvest them.
To the rest of the world, a dead Imp was just toxic garbage.
To Kaelen, it was an all-you-can-eat buffet of raw attributes.
He tapped the screen, selecting Task 114. The terminal issued a dull chime and printed a cheap paper permit.
"Hey, freshman," a voice called out from the corner of the room. An older student in a patched leather jacket was leaning against a concrete pillar, chewing on a toothpick. "You actually planning on taking that sub-basement job? Sector 9 cold storage has been locked up for months. It’s full of filth, and those Imps bite like hell. A Salvager alone down there is just begging to get their ankles chewed off."
Kaelen kept his expression perfectly flat, turning around with a look of mild, desperate anxiety—the exact look a broke, terrified Tier-E student should have.
"I... I need to pay for my meals for the week, senior," Kaelen said, lowering his shoulders to look smaller, humbler. "The paste rations aren't enough."
The older student snorted, shaking his head. "Suit yourself, kid. Just don't get trapped down there. Nobody's coming to rescue an auxiliary."
"Thank you for the warning, senior," Kaelen muttered, quickly stuffing the paper permit into his pocket and heading for the exit stairs.
As he stepped out into the chilly evening air of the slums, heading toward the abandoned warehouses of Sector 9, the anxiety vanished from his face, replaced by a cold, sharp focus. He adjusted his grip on the heavy iron crowbar he had rented from the equipment locker for two credits.
The cover was set. The hustle was about to begin.
